{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496837"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:58:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:58:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1424"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1424"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.07,0.65,0.23,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1424"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112755"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1424"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1424"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94789"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1641"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28404"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46350"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112755","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112755"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of shortness of breath and chest pain. He has a medical history of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease, deep venous thrombosis, myocardial infarction, and hypertension. His regular medications include omeprazole, amlodipine, atorvastatin, and aspirin. He recently flew home to Adelaide from a conference in Berlin. He reports having rhinorrhoea, myalgias, and low-grade fever during his trip. He does not smoke but drinks one glass of wine with most dinners.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Cardiorespiratory examination is unremarkable. An ECG is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atrial fibrillation","Anteroseptal ST-elevation myocardial infarction","Pulmonary embolism","Pericarditis","Pneumonia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute dyspnoea and chest pain following recent long-haul travel, with a significant history of deep venous thrombosis. These features strongly suggest pulmonary embolism (PE). The ECG shows the S1Q3T3 pattern - a prominent S wave in lead I, Q wave in lead III, and T wave inversion in lead III - which is a classic though uncommon finding in PE, occurring in only 10-20% of cases. In addition, there is widespread T-wave inversion, particularly in the precordial leads, with some also showing ST depression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given the combination of risk factors (previous DVT, recent long-haul flight), clinical presentation (acute dyspnoea and chest pain), and supportive ECG findings. While sinus tachycardia is the most common ECG finding in PE (present in up to 40% of cases), this patient\u0027s ECG demonstrates the S1Q3T3 pattern which, although less common, is more specific for PE when present. The S1Q3T3 pattern and other ECG changes in PE reflect acute right ventricular strain caused by increased afterload from embolic obstruction of pulmonary vessels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther ECG features suggesting right ventricular strain in PE include: right axis deviation, right bundle branch block (complete or incomplete), P pulmonale (peaked P waves in lead II), T wave inversions in the right precordial leads (V1-V4), and ST segment changes in these leads. These findings may appear in combination or isolation. It is important to note that a completely normal ECG can be seen in up to 30% of patients with PE, so the absence of ECG changes does not exclude the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of ECG evidence of right ventricular strain has important management implications. Patients with PE and signs of right ventricular dysfunction are at higher risk of adverse outcomes and may be candidates for more aggressive therapy. While most patients with PE are managed with anticoagulation alone, those with evidence of right ventricular strain on ECG (particularly when corroborated by echocardiography or elevated cardiac biomarkers) may require thrombolytic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrial fibrillation\u003C/strong\u003E would present with an irregularly irregular rhythm and absent P waves on ECG, neither of which are present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnteroseptal ST-elevation myocardial infarction\u003C/strong\u003E would show ST-segment elevation in leads V1-V4, which is not present here. While the patient has a history of myocardial infarction, the ECG findings are not consistent with acute STEMI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericarditis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with widespread concave ST elevation and PR depression across multiple leads. Although the patient had recent viral symptoms, the ECG findings do not support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E could explain the dyspnoea following upper respiratory symptoms, but would not typically cause the S1Q3T3 pattern on ECG, and the normal examination findings make this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sinus tachycardia is the most common ECG finding in pulmonary embolism, though a normal ECG does not exclude the diagnosis.","The S1Q3T3 pattern is specific but insensitive for pulmonary embolism, occurring in only 10-20% of cases.","ECG evidence of right ventricular strain in pulmonary embolism indicates a higher risk and may influence decisions regarding thrombolysis."],"references":["Shahani L. S1Q3T3 pattern leading to early diagnosis of pulmonary embolism. BMJ Case Rep. 2012 Jul 9;2012:bcr2012006569.","Boey E, Teo SG, Poh KK. Electrocardiographic findings in pulmonary embolism. Singapore Med J. 2015 Oct;56(10):533-7.","Thomson D, Kourounis G, Trenear R, Messow CM, Hrobar P, Mackay A, Isles C. ECG in suspected pulmonary embolism. Postgrad Med J. 2019 Jan;95(1119):12-17."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94789"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1424"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15360"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15360"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c00b4935-12ac-4cc3-b6a8-50dc8343a7fb.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c00b4935-12ac-4cc3-b6a8-50dc8343a7fb.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":756,"height":379}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94789"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-05T13:35:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-05T13:36:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1424"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112755"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"202